The cluster is built with dual-fabric redundancy across both Nexus switches. On the masters, the storage bond (bnd0 = eno7 + eno8) runs active-backup with one leg on each fabric. On the GPU workers, bond0 runs LACP at 100Gbps, again with one leg per fabric. Network team confirmed this is a rolling upgrade, one switch at a time, so storage and app VLAN traffic should fail over to the surviving link with only a few seconds of disruption. Running workloads, the MetalLB LoadBalancer services (MinIO, Milvus, PostgreSQL), and the GPU jobs should all stay up through it.
The gap we have is on the management network. Right now the masters are running on a single management NIC — eno5 on Fabric A. The Fabric B standby (eno6) is disabled because it was causing a MetalLB ARP conflict we haven't fully resolved yet. So while the Fabric A switch is rebooting, we'll lose the API VIP (10.172.248.155), the Ingress VIP (10.172.248.156), and the Gateway VIP (10.172.248.175). That means no oc CLI, no web console, no ArgoCD syncs, and no Gateway API routes during that window. Everything comes back as soon as the switch is back online, but it's worth calling out so people know what to expect.
I'm also going to hibernate the CloudNativePG clusters before the window and wake them up after. I don't want to take the chance of a database switchover getting triggered mid-maintenance while the network is unstable.
Before the window:

Hibernate the CNPG clusters in dev, test, and prod
Send a note to the users about the expected management access gap

After the window:

Check that all 5 nodes come back Ready
Run oc get co to make sure all cluster operators are healthy
Wake the CNPG clusters and make sure all instances come back up cleanly
Validate the MetalLB LoadBalancer services on all three app VLANs
Confirm ArgoCD apps are synced and healthy
Check that the Gateway API routes are responding
